The M.A. in Linguistics (Thesis) program provides training in the fundamentals
of theoretical and experimental linguistics.
The program culminates in the preparation of a thesis, which is written under
the direction of a supervisory committee, and which is expected to report
on original research outcomes of publishable quality.

The expected duration of the program is one year and eight months, starting
in September 2025 and concluding in April 2027.

27 credits are dedicated to courses, which includes 6 credits from the graduate
research seminar and 21 from a combination of required foundational courses and
additional upper-year courses.
18 credits are dedicated to research.